Build succeeded:
  * [Lint style](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/11191926075/job/31115453735)
  * [Build](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/11191926075/job/31115453809)

You've put this inside an (anonymous) section, when it doesn't use any of the section's variables. 

Much weaker typeclass assumptions would work, e.g. in this file `E''` is a generic NormedAddCommGroup and you can do
```
lemma isLittleO_id_nhdsWithin [One E''] [NeZero (1 : E'')] (s : Set E'') :
    id =o[𝓝[s] 0] (fun _ ↦ (1 : E'')) :=
  (isLittleO_id_const one_ne_zero).mono nhdsWithin_le_nhds
```
(it can infer the type of `id` from `s`). This will apply to `ℤ_[p]` for example, while your previous formulation wouldn't.

Generally I'm a little wary of having a special lemma for the "nhdsWithin" version; we could equally ask for a `nhdsWithin` variant of any of the (dozens? hundreds?) of lemmas about bigO/littleO/limits along neighbourhoods of something – where do you stop? Maybe let's add `isLittleO_id_one`, and inline the `nhdsWithin_le_nhds` at the point of use.

```suggestion
lemma isBigO_mul_iff_isBigO_div {f g h : α → 𝕜} (hf : ∀ᶠ x in l, f x ≠ 0) 
```
(this file is absolutely heaving with global variables, the existing `α` and `𝕜` fit)
I tried to find a slick way of doing this with "filter_upwards" but I didn't succeed, and this works. (It can be shortened with dot-notation but that makes it even less readable.)
